4084
4085SAFE_IDENTIFIER_RE = re.compile(r"^[_a-zA-Z][\w]*$")
4086
4087
4088@t.overload
4089def to_identifier(name: None, quoted: t.Optional[bool] = None) -> None:
4090    ...
4091
4092
4093@t.overload
4094def to_identifier(name: str | Identifier, quoted: t.Optional[bool] = None) -> Identifier:
4095    ...
4096
4097
4098def to_identifier(name, quoted=None):
4099    """Builds an identifier.
4100
4101    Args:
4102        name: The name to turn into an identifier.
4103        quoted: Whether or not force quote the identifier.
4104
4105    Returns:
4106        The identifier ast node.
4107    """
4108
4109    if name is None:
4110        return None
4111
4112    if isinstance(name, Identifier):
4113        identifier = name
4114    elif isinstance(name, str):
4115        identifier = Identifier(
4116            this=name,
4117            quoted=not re.match(SAFE_IDENTIFIER_RE, name) if quoted is None else quoted,
4118        )
4119    else:
4120        raise ValueError(f"Name needs to be a string or an Identifier, got: {name.__class__}")
4121    return identifier
4122
4123
4124INTERVAL_STRING_RE = re.compile(r"\s*([0-9]+)\s*([a-zA-Z]+)\s*")
4125
4126
4127def to_interval(interval: str | Literal) -> Interval:
4128    """Builds an interval expression from a string like '1 day' or '5 months'."""
4129    if isinstance(interval, Literal):
4130        if not interval.is_string:
4131            raise ValueError("Invalid interval string.")
4132
4133        interval = interval.this
4134
4135    interval_parts = INTERVAL_STRING_RE.match(interval)  # type: ignore
4136
4137    if not interval_parts:
4138        raise ValueError("Invalid interval string.")
4139
4140    return Interval(
4141        this=Literal.string(interval_parts.group(1)),
4142        unit=Var(this=interval_parts.group(2)),
4143    )
4144
4145
4146@t.overload
4147def to_table(sql_path: str | Table, **kwargs) -> Table:
4148    ...
4149
4150
4151@t.overload
4152def to_table(sql_path: None, **kwargs) -> None:
4153    ...
4154
4155
4156def to_table(sql_path: t.Optional[str | Table], **kwargs) -> t.Optional[Table]:
4157    """
4158    Create a table expression from a `[catalog].[schema].[table]` sql path. Catalog and schema are optional.
4159    If a table is passed in then that table is returned.
4160
4161    Args:
4162        sql_path: a `[catalog].[schema].[table]` string.
4163
4164    Returns:
4165        A table expression.
4166    """
4167    if sql_path is None or isinstance(sql_path, Table):
4168        return sql_path
4169    if not isinstance(sql_path, str):
4170        raise ValueError(f"Invalid type provided for a table: {type(sql_path)}")
4171
4172    catalog, db, table_name = (to_identifier(x) for x in split_num_words(sql_path, ".", 3))
4173    return Table(this=table_name, db=db, catalog=catalog, **kwargs)
4174
4175
4176def to_column(sql_path: str | Column, **kwargs) -> Column:
4177    """
4178    Create a column from a `[table].[column]` sql path. Schema is optional.
4179
4180    If a column is passed in then that column is returned.
4181
4182    Args:
4183        sql_path: `[table].[column]` string
4184    Returns:
4185        Table: A column expression
4186    """
4187    if sql_path is None or isinstance(sql_path, Column):
4188        return sql_path
4189    if not isinstance(sql_path, str):
4190        raise ValueError(f"Invalid type provided for column: {type(sql_path)}")
4191    table_name, column_name = (to_identifier(x) for x in split_num_words(sql_path, ".", 2))
4192    return Column(this=column_name, table=table_name, **kwargs)
4193
4194
4195def alias_(
4196    expression: str | Expression,
4197    alias: str | Identifier,
4198    table: bool | t.Sequence[str | Identifier] = False,
4199    quoted: t.Optional[bool] = None,
4200    dialect: DialectType = None,
4201    **opts,
4202):
4203    """Create an Alias expression.
4204
4205    Example:
4206        >>> alias_('foo', 'bar').sql()
4207        'foo AS bar'
4208
4209        >>> alias_('(select 1, 2)', 'bar', table=['a', 'b']).sql()
4210        '(SELECT 1, 2) AS bar(a, b)'
4211
4212    Args:
4213        expression: the SQL code strings to parse.
4214            If an Expression instance is passed, this is used as-is.
4215        alias: the alias name to use. If the name has
4216            special characters it is quoted.
4217        table: Whether or not to create a table alias, can also be a list of columns.
4218        quoted: whether or not to quote the alias
4219        dialect: the dialect used to parse the input expression.
4220        **opts: other options to use to parse the input expressions.
4221
4222    Returns:
4223        Alias: the aliased expression
4224    """
4225    exp = maybe_parse(expression, dialect=dialect, **opts)
4226    alias = to_identifier(alias, quoted=quoted)
4227
4228    if table:
4229        table_alias = TableAlias(this=alias)
4230        exp.set("alias", table_alias)
4231
4232        if not isinstance(table, bool):
4233            for column in table:
4234                table_alias.append("columns", to_identifier(column, quoted=quoted))
4235
4236        return exp
4237
4238    # We don't set the "alias" arg for Window expressions, because that would add an IDENTIFIER node in
4239    # the AST, representing a "named_window" [1] construct (eg. bigquery). What we want is an ALIAS node
4240    # for the complete Window expression.
4241    #
4242    # [1]: https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/docs/reference/standard-sql/window-function-calls
4243
4244    if "alias" in exp.arg_types and not isinstance(exp, Window):
4245        exp = exp.copy()
4246        exp.set("alias", alias)
4247        return exp
4248    return Alias(this=exp, alias=alias)
4249
4250
4251def subquery(expression, alias=None, dialect=None, **opts):
4252    """
4253    Build a subquery expression.
4254
4255    Example:
4256        >>> subquery('select x from tbl', 'bar').select('x').sql()
4257        'SELECT x FROM (SELECT x FROM tbl) AS bar'
4258
4259    Args:
4260        expression (str | Expression): the SQL code strings to parse.
4261            If an Expression instance is passed, this is used as-is.
4262        alias (str | Expression): the alias name to use.
4263        dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
4264        **opts: other options to use to parse the input expressions.
4265
4266    Returns:
4267        Select: a new select with the subquery expression included
4268    """
4269
4270    expression = maybe_parse(expression, dialect=dialect, **opts).subquery(alias)
4271    return Select().from_(expression, dialect=dialect, **opts)
4272
4273
4274def column(col, table=None, quoted=None) -> Column:
4275    """
4276    Build a Column.
4277
4278    Args:
4279        col (str | Expression): column name
4280        table (str | Expression): table name
4281    Returns:
4282        Column: column instance
4283    """
4284    return Column(
4285        this=to_identifier(col, quoted=quoted),
4286        table=to_identifier(table, quoted=quoted),
4287    )

4289
4290def cast(expression: str | Expression, to: str | DataType | DataType.Type, **opts) -> Cast:
4291    """Cast an expression to a data type.
4292
4293    Example:
4294        >>> cast('x + 1', 'int').sql()
4295        'CAST(x + 1 AS INT)'
4296
4297    Args:
4298        expression: The expression to cast.
4299        to: The datatype to cast to.
4300
4301    Returns:
4302        A cast node.
4303    """
4304    expression = maybe_parse(expression, **opts)
4305    return Cast(this=expression, to=DataType.build(to, **opts))

4307
4308def table_(table, db=None, catalog=None, quoted=None, alias=None) -> Table:
4309    """Build a Table.
4310
4311    Args:
4312        table (str | Expression): column name
4313        db (str | Expression): db name
4314        catalog (str | Expression): catalog name
4315
4316    Returns:
4317        Table: table instance
4318    """
4319    return Table(
4320        this=to_identifier(table, quoted=quoted),
4321        db=to_identifier(db, quoted=quoted),
4322        catalog=to_identifier(catalog, quoted=quoted),
4323        alias=TableAlias(this=to_identifier(alias)) if alias else None,
4324    )

4326
4327def values(
4328    values: t.Iterable[t.Tuple[t.Any, ...]],
4329    alias: t.Optional[str] = None,
4330    columns: t.Optional[t.Iterable[str] | t.Dict[str, DataType]] = None,
4331) -> Values:
4332    """Build VALUES statement.
4333
4334    Example:
4335        >>> values([(1, '2')]).sql()
4336        "VALUES (1, '2')"
4337
4338    Args:
4339        values: values statements that will be converted to SQL
4340        alias: optional alias
4341        columns: Optional list of ordered column names or ordered dictionary of column names to types.
4342         If either are provided then an alias is also required.
4343         If a dictionary is provided then the first column of the values will be casted to the expected type
4344         in order to help with type inference.
4345
4346    Returns:
4347        Values: the Values expression object
4348    """
4349    if columns and not alias:
4350        raise ValueError("Alias is required when providing columns")
4351    table_alias = (
4352        TableAlias(this=to_identifier(alias), columns=[to_identifier(x) for x in columns])
4353        if columns
4354        else TableAlias(this=to_identifier(alias) if alias else None)
4355    )
4356    expressions = [convert(tup) for tup in values]
4357    if columns and isinstance(columns, dict):
4358        types = list(columns.values())
4359        expressions[0].set(
4360            "expressions",
4361            [cast(x, types[i]) for i, x in enumerate(expressions[0].expressions)],
4362        )
4363    return Values(
4364        expressions=expressions,
4365        alias=table_alias,
4366    )
4367
4368
4369def rename_table(old_name: str | Table, new_name: str | Table) -> AlterTable:
4370    """Build ALTER TABLE... RENAME... expression
4371
4372    Args:
4373        old_name: The old name of the table
4374        new_name: The new name of the table
4375
4376    Returns:
4377        Alter table expression
4378    """
4379    old_table = to_table(old_name)
4380    new_table = to_table(new_name)
4381    return AlterTable(
4382        this=old_table,
4383        actions=[
4384            RenameTable(this=new_table),
4385        ],
4386    )
4387
4388
4389def convert(value) -> Expression:
4390    """Convert a python value into an expression object.
4391
4392    Raises an error if a conversion is not possible.
4393
4394    Args:
4395        value (Any): a python object
4396
4397    Returns:
4398        Expression: the equivalent expression object
4399    """
4400    if isinstance(value, Expression):
4401        return value
4402    if value is None:
4403        return NULL
4404    if isinstance(value, bool):
4405        return Boolean(this=value)
4406    if isinstance(value, str):
4407        return Literal.string(value)
4408    if isinstance(value, float) and math.isnan(value):
4409        return NULL
4410    if isinstance(value, numbers.Number):
4411        return Literal.number(value)
4412    if isinstance(value, tuple):
4413        return Tuple(expressions=[convert(v) for v in value])
4414    if isinstance(value, list):
4415        return Array(expressions=[convert(v) for v in value])
4416    if isinstance(value, dict):
4417        return Map(
4418            keys=[convert(k) for k in value],
4419            values=[convert(v) for v in value.values()],
4420        )
4421    if isinstance(value, datetime.datetime):
4422        datetime_literal = Literal.string(
4423            (value if value.tzinfo else value.replace(tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc)).isoformat()
4424        )
4425        return TimeStrToTime(this=datetime_literal)
4426    if isinstance(value, datetime.date):
4427        date_literal = Literal.string(value.strftime("%Y-%m-%d"))
4428        return DateStrToDate(this=date_literal)
4429    raise ValueError(f"Cannot convert {value}")
4430
4431
4432def replace_children(expression, fun):
4433    """
4434    Replace children of an expression with the result of a lambda fun(child) -> exp.
4435    """
4436    for k, v in expression.args.items():
4437        is_list_arg = isinstance(v, list)
4438
4439        child_nodes = v if is_list_arg else [v]
4440        new_child_nodes = []
4441
4442        for cn in child_nodes:
4443            if isinstance(cn, Expression):
4444                for child_node in ensure_collection(fun(cn)):
4445                    new_child_nodes.append(child_node)
4446                    child_node.parent = expression
4447                    child_node.arg_key = k
4448            else:
4449                new_child_nodes.append(cn)
4450
4451        expression.args[k] = new_child_nodes if is_list_arg else seq_get(new_child_nodes, 0)
4452
4453
4454def column_table_names(expression):
4455    """
4456    Return all table names referenced through columns in an expression.
4457
4458    Example:
4459        >>> import sqlglot
4460        >>> column_table_names(sqlglot.parse_one("a.b AND c.d AND c.e"))
4461        ['c', 'a']
4462
4463    Args:
4464        expression (sqlglot.Expression): expression to find table names
4465
4466    Returns:
4467        list: A list of unique names
4468    """
4469    return list(dict.fromkeys(column.table for column in expression.find_all(Column)))
4470
4471
4472def table_name(table) -> str:
4473    """Get the full name of a table as a string.
4474
4475    Args:
4476        table (exp.Table | str): table expression node or string.
4477
4478    Examples:
4479        >>> from sqlglot import exp, parse_one
4480        >>> table_name(parse_one("select * from a.b.c").find(exp.Table))
4481        'a.b.c'
4482
4483    Returns:
4484        The table name.
4485    """
4486
4487    table = maybe_parse(table, into=Table)
4488
4489    if not table:
4490        raise ValueError(f"Cannot parse {table}")
4491
4492    return ".".join(
4493        part
4494        for part in (
4495            table.text("catalog"),
4496            table.text("db"),
4497            table.name,
4498        )
4499        if part
4500    )
4501
4502
4503def replace_tables(expression, mapping):
4504    """Replace all tables in expression according to the mapping.
4505
4506    Args:
4507        expression (sqlglot.Expression): expression node to be transformed and replaced.
4508        mapping (Dict[str, str]): mapping of table names.
4509
4510    Examples:
4511        >>> from sqlglot import exp, parse_one
4512        >>> replace_tables(parse_one("select * from a.b"), {"a.b": "c"}).sql()
4513        'SELECT * FROM c'
4514
4515    Returns:
4516        The mapped expression.
4517    """
4518
4519    def _replace_tables(node):
4520        if isinstance(node, Table):
4521            new_name = mapping.get(table_name(node))
4522            if new_name:
4523                return to_table(
4524                    new_name,
4525                    **{k: v for k, v in node.args.items() if k not in ("this", "db", "catalog")},
4526                )
4527        return node
4528
4529    return expression.transform(_replace_tables)
4530
4531
4532def replace_placeholders(expression, *args, **kwargs):
4533    """Replace placeholders in an expression.
4534
4535    Args:
4536        expression (sqlglot.Expression): expression node to be transformed and replaced.
4537        args: positional names that will substitute unnamed placeholders in the given order.
4538        kwargs: keyword arguments that will substitute named placeholders.
4539
4540    Examples:
4541        >>> from sqlglot import exp, parse_one
4542        >>> replace_placeholders(
4543        ...     parse_one("select * from :tbl where ? = ?"), "a", "b", tbl="foo"
4544        ... ).sql()
4545        'SELECT * FROM foo WHERE a = b'
4546
4547    Returns:
4548        The mapped expression.
4549    """
4550
4551    def _replace_placeholders(node, args, **kwargs):
4552        if isinstance(node, Placeholder):
4553            if node.name:
4554                new_name = kwargs.get(node.name)
4555                if new_name:
4556                    return to_identifier(new_name)
4557            else:
4558                try:
4559                    return to_identifier(next(args))
4560                except StopIteration:
4561                    pass
4562        return node
4563
4564    return expression.transform(_replace_placeholders, iter(args), **kwargs)
4565
4566
4567def expand(expression: Expression, sources: t.Dict[str, Subqueryable], copy=True) -> Expression:
4568    """Transforms an expression by expanding all referenced sources into subqueries.
4569
4570    Examples:
4571        >>> from sqlglot import parse_one
4572        >>> expand(parse_one("select * from x AS z"), {"x": parse_one("select * from y")}).sql()
4573        'SELECT * FROM (SELECT * FROM y) AS z /* source: x */'
4574
4575    Args:
4576        expression: The expression to expand.
4577        sources: A dictionary of name to Subqueryables.
4578        copy: Whether or not to copy the expression during transformation. Defaults to True.
4579
4580    Returns:
4581        The transformed expression.
4582    """
4583
4584    def _expand(node: Expression):
4585        if isinstance(node, Table):
4586            name = table_name(node)
4587            source = sources.get(name)
4588            if source:
4589                subquery = source.subquery(node.alias or name)
4590                subquery.comments = [f"source: {name}"]
4591                return subquery
4592        return node
4593
4594    return expression.transform(_expand, copy=copy)
4595
4596
4597def func(name: str, *args, dialect: DialectType = None, **kwargs) -> Func:
4598    """
4599    Returns a Func expression.
4600
4601    Examples:
4602        >>> func("abs", 5).sql()
4603        'ABS(5)'
4604
4605        >>> func("cast", this=5, to=DataType.build("DOUBLE")).sql()
4606        'CAST(5 AS DOUBLE)'
4607
4608    Args:
4609        name: the name of the function to build.
4610        args: the args used to instantiate the function of interest.
4611        dialect: the source dialect.
4612        kwargs: the kwargs used to instantiate the function of interest.
4613
4614    Note:
4615        The arguments `args` and `kwargs` are mutually exclusive.
4616
4617    Returns:
4618        An instance of the function of interest, or an anonymous function, if `name` doesn't
4619        correspond to an existing `sqlglot.expressions.Func` class.
4620    """
4621    if args and kwargs:
4622        raise ValueError("Can't use both args and kwargs to instantiate a function.")
4623
4624    from sqlglot.dialects.dialect import Dialect
4625
4626    args = tuple(convert(arg) for arg in args)
4627    kwargs = {key: convert(value) for key, value in kwargs.items()}
4628
4629    parser = Dialect.get_or_raise(dialect)().parser()
4630    from_args_list = parser.FUNCTIONS.get(name.upper())
4631
4632    if from_args_list:
4633        function = from_args_list(args) if args else from_args_list.__self__(**kwargs)  # type: ignore
4634    else:
4635        kwargs = kwargs or {"expressions": args}
4636        function = Anonymous(this=name, **kwargs)
4637
4638    for error_message in function.error_messages(args):
4639        raise ValueError(error_message)
4640
4641    return function
4642
4643
4644def true():
4645    """
4646    Returns a true Boolean expression.
4647    """
4648    return Boolean(this=True)
4649
4650
4651def false():
4652    """
4653    Returns a false Boolean expression.
4654    """
4655    return Boolean(this=False)
4656
4657
4658def null():
4659    """
4660    Returns a Null expression.
4661    """
4662    return Null()
4663
4664
4665# TODO: deprecate this
4666TRUE = Boolean(this=True)
4667FALSE = Boolean(this=False)
4668NULL = Null()
class Expression: 
 54class Expression(metaclass=_Expression):
 55    """
 56    The base class for all expressions in a syntax tree. Each Expression encapsulates any necessary
 57    context, such as its child expressions, their names (arg keys), and whether a given child expression
 58    is optional or not.
 59
 60    Attributes:
 61        key: a unique key for each class in the Expression hierarchy. This is useful for hashing
 62            and representing expressions as strings.
 63        arg_types: determines what arguments (child nodes) are supported by an expression. It
 64            maps arg keys to booleans that indicate whether the corresponding args are optional.
 65
 66    Example:
 67        >>> class Foo(Expression):
 68        ...     arg_types = {"this": True, "expression": False}
 69
 70        The above definition informs us that Foo is an Expression that requires an argument called
 71        "this" and may also optionally receive an argument called "expression".
 72
 73    Args:
 74        args: a mapping used for retrieving the arguments of an expression, given their arg keys.
 75        parent: a reference to the parent expression (or None, in case of root expressions).
 76        arg_key: the arg key an expression is associated with, i.e. the name its parent expression
 77            uses to refer to it.
 78        comments: a list of comments that are associated with a given expression. This is used in
 79            order to preserve comments when transpiling SQL code.
 80        _type: the `sqlglot.expressions.DataType` type of an expression. This is inferred by the
 81            optimizer, in order to enable some transformations that require type information.
 82    """
 83
 84    key = "expression"
 85    arg_types = {"this": True}
 86    __slots__ = ("args", "parent", "arg_key", "comments", "_type")
 87
 88    def __init__(self, **args: t.Any):
 89        self.args: t.Dict[str, t.Any] = args
 90        self.parent: t.Optional[Expression] = None
 91        self.arg_key: t.Optional[str] = None
 92        self.comments: t.Optional[t.List[str]] = None
 93        self._type: t.Optional[DataType] = None
 94
 95        for arg_key, value in self.args.items():
 96            self._set_parent(arg_key, value)
 97
 98    def __eq__(self, other) -> bool:
 99        return type(self) is type(other) and _norm_args(self) == _norm_args(other)
100
101    def __hash__(self) -> int:
102        return hash(
103            (
104                self.key,
105                tuple(
106                    (k, tuple(v) if isinstance(v, list) else v) for k, v in _norm_args(self).items()
107                ),
108            )
109        )
110
111    @property
112    def this(self):
113        """
114        Retrieves the argument with key "this".
115        """
116        return self.args.get("this")
117
118    @property
119    def expression(self):
120        """
121        Retrieves the argument with key "expression".
122        """
123        return self.args.get("expression")
124
125    @property
126    def expressions(self):
127        """
128        Retrieves the argument with key "expressions".
129        """
130        return self.args.get("expressions") or []
131
132    def text(self, key):
133        """
134        Returns a textual representation of the argument corresponding to "key". This can only be used
135        for args that are strings or leaf Expression instances, such as identifiers and literals.
136        """
137        field = self.args.get(key)
138        if isinstance(field, str):
139            return field
140        if isinstance(field, (Identifier, Literal, Var)):
141            return field.this
142        if isinstance(field, (Star, Null)):
143            return field.name
144        return ""
145
146    @property
147    def is_string(self):
148        """
149        Checks whether a Literal expression is a string.
150        """
151        return isinstance(self, Literal) and self.args["is_string"]
152
153    @property
154    def is_number(self):
155        """
156        Checks whether a Literal expression is a number.
157        """
158        return isinstance(self, Literal) and not self.args["is_string"]
159
160    @property
161    def is_int(self):
162        """
163        Checks whether a Literal expression is an integer.
164        """
165        if self.is_number:
166            try:
167                int(self.name)
168                return True
169            except ValueError:
170                pass
171        return False
172
173    @property
174    def alias(self):
175        """
176        Returns the alias of the expression, or an empty string if it's not aliased.
177        """
178        if isinstance(self.args.get("alias"), TableAlias):
179            return self.args["alias"].name
180        return self.text("alias")
181
182    @property
183    def name(self) -> str:
184        return self.text("this")
185
186    @property
187    def alias_or_name(self):
188        return self.alias or self.name
189
190    @property
191    def output_name(self):
192        """
193        Name of the output column if this expression is a selection.
194
195        If the Expression has no output name, an empty string is returned.
196
197        Example:
198            >>> from sqlglot import parse_one
199            >>> parse_one("SELECT a").expressions[0].output_name
200            'a'
201            >>> parse_one("SELECT b AS c").expressions[0].output_name
202            'c'
203            >>> parse_one("SELECT 1 + 2").expressions[0].output_name
204            ''
205        """
206        return ""
207
208    @property
209    def type(self) -> t.Optional[DataType]:
210        return self._type
211
212    @type.setter
213    def type(self, dtype: t.Optional[DataType | DataType.Type | str]) -> None:
214        if dtype and not isinstance(dtype, DataType):
215            dtype = DataType.build(dtype)
216        self._type = dtype  # type: ignore
217
218    def __deepcopy__(self, memo):
219        copy = self.__class__(**deepcopy(self.args))
220        copy.comments = self.comments
221        copy.type = self.type
222        return copy
223
224    def copy(self):
225        """
226        Returns a deep copy of the expression.
227        """
228        new = deepcopy(self)
229        new.parent = self.parent
230        for item, parent, _ in new.bfs():
231            if isinstance(item, Expression) and parent:
232                item.parent = parent
233        return new
234
235    def append(self, arg_key, value):
236        """
237        Appends value to arg_key if it's a list or sets it as a new list.
238
239        Args:
240            arg_key (str): name of the list expression arg
241            value (Any): value to append to the list
242        """
243        if not isinstance(self.args.get(arg_key), list):
244            self.args[arg_key] = []
245        self.args[arg_key].append(value)
246        self._set_parent(arg_key, value)
247
248    def set(self, arg_key, value):
249        """
250        Sets `arg_key` to `value`.
251
252        Args:
253            arg_key (str): name of the expression arg.
254            value: value to set the arg to.
255        """
256        self.args[arg_key] = value
257        self._set_parent(arg_key, value)
258
259    def _set_parent(self, arg_key, value):
260        if isinstance(value, Expression):
261            value.parent = self
262            value.arg_key = arg_key
263        elif isinstance(value, list):
264            for v in value:
265                if isinstance(v, Expression):
266                    v.parent = self
267                    v.arg_key = arg_key
268
269    @property
270    def depth(self):
271        """
272        Returns the depth of this tree.
273        """
274        if self.parent:
275            return self.parent.depth + 1
276        return 0
277
278    def find(self, *expression_types, bfs=True):
279        """
280        Returns the first node in this tree which matches at least one of
281        the specified types.
282
283        Args:
284            expression_types (type): the expression type(s) to match.
285
286        Returns:
287            The node which matches the criteria or None if no such node was found.
288        """
289        return next(self.find_all(*expression_types, bfs=bfs), None)
290
291    def find_all(self, *expression_types, bfs=True):
292        """
293        Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree and only
294        yields those that match at least one of the specified expression types.
295
296        Args:
297            expression_types (type): the expression type(s) to match.
298
299        Returns:
300            The generator object.
301        """
302        for expression, _, _ in self.walk(bfs=bfs):
303            if isinstance(expression, expression_types):
304                yield expression
305
306    def find_ancestor(self, *expression_types):
307        """
308        Returns a nearest parent matching expression_types.
309
310        Args:
311            expression_types (type): the expression type(s) to match.
312
313        Returns:
314            The parent node.
315        """
316        ancestor = self.parent
317        while ancestor and not isinstance(ancestor, expression_types):
318            ancestor = ancestor.parent
319        return ancestor
320
321    @property
322    def parent_select(self):
323        """
324        Returns the parent select statement.
325        """
326        return self.find_ancestor(Select)
327
328    def walk(self, bfs=True, prune=None):
329        """
330        Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree.
331
332        Args:
333            bfs (bool): if set to True the BFS traversal order will be applied,
334                otherwise the DFS traversal will be used instead.
335            prune ((node, parent, arg_key) -> bool): callable that returns True if
336                the generator should stop traversing this branch of the tree.
337
338        Returns:
339            the generator object.
340        """
341        if bfs:
342            yield from self.bfs(prune=prune)
343        else:
344            yield from self.dfs(prune=prune)
345
346    def dfs(self, parent=None, key=None, prune=None):
347        """
348        Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree in
349        the DFS (Depth-first) order.
350
351        Returns:
352            The generator object.
353        """
354        parent = parent or self.parent
355        yield self, parent, key
356        if prune and prune(self, parent, key):
357            return
358
359        for k, v in self.args.items():
360            for node in ensure_collection(v):
361                if isinstance(node, Expression):
362                    yield from node.dfs(self, k, prune)
363
364    def bfs(self, prune=None):
365        """
366        Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree in
367        the BFS (Breadth-first) order.
368
369        Returns:
370            The generator object.
371        """
372        queue = deque([(self, self.parent, None)])
373
374        while queue:
375            item, parent, key = queue.popleft()
376
377            yield item, parent, key
378            if prune and prune(item, parent, key):
379                continue
380
381            if isinstance(item, Expression):
382                for k, v in item.args.items():
383                    for node in ensure_collection(v):
384                        if isinstance(node, Expression):
385                            queue.append((node, item, k))
386
387    def unnest(self):
388        """
389        Returns the first non parenthesis child or self.
390        """
391        expression = self
392        while isinstance(expression, Paren):
393            expression = expression.this
394        return expression
395
396    def unalias(self):
397        """
398        Returns the inner expression if this is an Alias.
399        """
400        if isinstance(self, Alias):
401            return self.this
402        return self
403
404    def unnest_operands(self):
405        """
406        Returns unnested operands as a tuple.
407        """
408        return tuple(arg.unnest() for arg in self.args.values() if arg)
409
410    def flatten(self, unnest=True):
411        """
412        Returns a generator which yields child nodes who's parents are the same class.
413
414        A AND B AND C -> [A, B, C]
415        """
416        for node, _, _ in self.dfs(prune=lambda n, p, *_: p and not isinstance(n, self.__class__)):
417            if not isinstance(node, self.__class__):
418                yield node.unnest() if unnest else node
419
420    def __str__(self):
421        return self.sql()
422
423    def __repr__(self):
424        return self._to_s()
425
426    def sql(self, dialect: DialectType = None, **opts) -> str:
427        """
428        Returns SQL string representation of this tree.
429
430        Args:
431            dialect: the dialect of the output SQL string (eg. "spark", "hive", "presto", "mysql").
432            opts: other `sqlglot.generator.Generator` options.
433
434        Returns:
435            The SQL string.
436        """
437        from sqlglot.dialects import Dialect
438
439        return Dialect.get_or_raise(dialect)().generate(self, **opts)
440
441    def _to_s(self, hide_missing: bool = True, level: int = 0) -> str:
442        indent = "" if not level else "\n"
443        indent += "".join(["  "] * level)
444        left = f"({self.key.upper()} "
445
446        args: t.Dict[str, t.Any] = {
447            k: ", ".join(
448                v._to_s(hide_missing=hide_missing, level=level + 1)
449                if hasattr(v, "_to_s")
450                else str(v)
451                for v in ensure_collection(vs)
452                if v is not None
453            )
454            for k, vs in self.args.items()
455        }
456        args["comments"] = self.comments
457        args["type"] = self.type
458        args = {k: v for k, v in args.items() if v or not hide_missing}
459
460        right = ", ".join(f"{k}: {v}" for k, v in args.items())
461        right += ")"
462
463        return indent + left + right
464
465    def transform(self, fun, *args, copy=True, **kwargs):
466        """
467        Recursively visits all tree nodes (excluding already transformed ones)
468        and applies the given transformation function to each node.
469
470        Args:
471            fun (function): a function which takes a node as an argument and returns a
472                new transformed node or the same node without modifications. If the function
473                returns None, then the corresponding node will be removed from the syntax tree.
474            copy (bool): if set to True a new tree instance is constructed, otherwise the tree is
475                modified in place.
476
477        Returns:
478            The transformed tree.
479        """
480        node = self.copy() if copy else self
481        new_node = fun(node, *args, **kwargs)
482
483        if new_node is None or not isinstance(new_node, Expression):
484            return new_node
485        if new_node is not node:
486            new_node.parent = node.parent
487            return new_node
488
489        replace_children(new_node, lambda child: child.transform(fun, *args, copy=False, **kwargs))
490        return new_node
491
492    def replace(self, expression):
493        """
494        Swap out this expression with a new expression.
495
496        For example::
497
498            >>> tree = Select().select("x").from_("tbl")
499            >>> tree.find(Column).replace(Column(this="y"))
500            (COLUMN this: y)
501            >>> tree.sql()
502            'SELECT y FROM tbl'
503
504        Args:
505            expression (Expression|None): new node
506
507        Returns:
508            The new expression or expressions.
509        """
510        if not self.parent:
511            return expression
512
513        parent = self.parent
514        self.parent = None
515
516        replace_children(parent, lambda child: expression if child is self else child)
517        return expression
518
519    def pop(self):
520        """
521        Remove this expression from its AST.
522        """
523        self.replace(None)
524
525    def assert_is(self, type_):
526        """
527        Assert that this `Expression` is an instance of `type_`.
528
529        If it is NOT an instance of `type_`, this raises an assertion error.
530        Otherwise, this returns this expression.
531
532        Examples:
533            This is useful for type security in chained expressions:
534
535            >>> import sqlglot
536            >>> sqlglot.parse_one("SELECT x from y").assert_is(Select).select("z").sql()
537            'SELECT x, z FROM y'
538        """
539        assert isinstance(self, type_)
540        return self
541
542    def error_messages(self, args: t.Optional[t.Sequence] = None) -> t.List[str]:
543        """
544        Checks if this expression is valid (e.g. all mandatory args are set).
545
546        Args:
547            args: a sequence of values that were used to instantiate a Func expression. This is used
548                to check that the provided arguments don't exceed the function argument limit.
549
550        Returns:
551            A list of error messages for all possible errors that were found.
552        """
553        errors: t.List[str] = []
554
555        for k in self.args:
556            if k not in self.arg_types:
557                errors.append(f"Unexpected keyword: '{k}' for {self.__class__}")
558        for k, mandatory in self.arg_types.items():
559            v = self.args.get(k)
560            if mandatory and (v is None or (isinstance(v, list) and not v)):
561                errors.append(f"Required keyword: '{k}' missing for {self.__class__}")
562
563        if (
564            args
565            and isinstance(self, Func)
566            and len(args) > len(self.arg_types)
567            and not self.is_var_len_args
568        ):
569            errors.append(
570                f"The number of provided arguments ({len(args)}) is greater than "
571                f"the maximum number of supported arguments ({len(self.arg_types)})"
572            )
573
574        return errors
575
576    def dump(self):
577        """
578        Dump this Expression to a JSON-serializable dict.
579        """
580        from sqlglot.serde import dump
581
582        return dump(self)
583
584    @classmethod
585    def load(cls, obj):
586        """
587        Load a dict (as returned by `Expression.dump`) into an Expression instance.
588        """
589        from sqlglot.serde import load
590
591        return load(obj)

The base class for all expressions in a syntax tree. Each Expression encapsulates any necessary context, such as its child expressions, their names (arg keys), and whether a given child expression is optional or not.

Attributes:
  • key: a unique key for each class in the Expression hierarchy. This is useful for hashing and representing expressions as strings.
  • arg_types: determines what arguments (child nodes) are supported by an expression. It maps arg keys to booleans that indicate whether the corresponding args are optional.
Example:
>>> class Foo(Expression):
...     arg_types = {"this": True, "expression": False}

The above definition informs us that Foo is an Expression that requires an argument called "this" and may also optionally receive an argument called "expression".

Arguments:
  • args: a mapping used for retrieving the arguments of an expression, given their arg keys.
  • parent: a reference to the parent expression (or None, in case of root expressions).
  • arg_key: the arg key an expression is associated with, i.e. the name its parent expression uses to refer to it.
  • comments: a list of comments that are associated with a given expression. This is used in order to preserve comments when transpiling SQL code.
  • _type: the sqlglot.expressions.DataType type of an expression. This is inferred by the optimizer, in order to enable some transformations that require type information.
Expression(**args: Any) 
88    def __init__(self, **args: t.Any):
89        self.args: t.Dict[str, t.Any] = args
90        self.parent: t.Optional[Expression] = None
91        self.arg_key: t.Optional[str] = None
92        self.comments: t.Optional[t.List[str]] = None
93        self._type: t.Optional[DataType] = None
94
95        for arg_key, value in self.args.items():
96            self._set_parent(arg_key, value)

def text(self, key): 
132    def text(self, key):
133        """
134        Returns a textual representation of the argument corresponding to "key". This can only be used
135        for args that are strings or leaf Expression instances, such as identifiers and literals.
136        """
137        field = self.args.get(key)
138        if isinstance(field, str):
139            return field
140        if isinstance(field, (Identifier, Literal, Var)):
141            return field.this
142        if isinstance(field, (Star, Null)):
143            return field.name
144        return ""

Returns a textual representation of the argument corresponding to "key". This can only be used for args that are strings or leaf Expression instances, such as identifiers and literals.

Checks whether a Literal expression is a string.

is_number

Checks whether a Literal expression is a number.

is_int

Checks whether a Literal expression is an integer.

alias

Returns the alias of the expression, or an empty string if it's not aliased.

output_name

Name of the output column if this expression is a selection.

If the Expression has no output name, an empty string is returned.

Example:
>>> from sqlglot import parse_one
>>> parse_one("SELECT a").expressions[0].output_name
'a'
>>> parse_one("SELECT b AS c").expressions[0].output_name
'c'
>>> parse_one("SELECT 1 + 2").expressions[0].output_name
''
def copy(self): 
224    def copy(self):
225        """
226        Returns a deep copy of the expression.
227        """
228        new = deepcopy(self)
229        new.parent = self.parent
230        for item, parent, _ in new.bfs():
231            if isinstance(item, Expression) and parent:
232                item.parent = parent
233        return new

Returns a deep copy of the expression.

def find_all(self, *expression_types, bfs=True): 
291    def find_all(self, *expression_types, bfs=True):
292        """
293        Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree and only
294        yields those that match at least one of the specified expression types.
295
296        Args:
297            expression_types (type): the expression type(s) to match.
298
299        Returns:
300            The generator object.
301        """
302        for expression, _, _ in self.walk(bfs=bfs):
303            if isinstance(expression, expression_types):
304                yield expression

def find_ancestor(self, *expression_types): 
306    def find_ancestor(self, *expression_types):
307        """
308        Returns a nearest parent matching expression_types.
309
310        Args:
311            expression_types (type): the expression type(s) to match.
312
313        Returns:
314            The parent node.
315        """
316        ancestor = self.parent
317        while ancestor and not isinstance(ancestor, expression_types):
318            ancestor = ancestor.parent
319        return ancestor

def walk(self, bfs=True, prune=None): 
328    def walk(self, bfs=True, prune=None):
329        """
330        Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree.
331
332        Args:
333            bfs (bool): if set to True the BFS traversal order will be applied,
334                otherwise the DFS traversal will be used instead.
335            prune ((node, parent, arg_key) -> bool): callable that returns True if
336                the generator should stop traversing this branch of the tree.
337
338        Returns:
339            the generator object.
340        """
341        if bfs:
342            yield from self.bfs(prune=prune)
343        else:
344            yield from self.dfs(prune=prune)

Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree.

Arguments:
  • bfs (bool): if set to True the BFS traversal order will be applied, otherwise the DFS traversal will be used instead.
  • prune ((node, parent, arg_key) -> bool): callable that returns True if the generator should stop traversing this branch of the tree.
Returns:

the generator object.

def dfs(self, parent=None, key=None, prune=None): 
346    def dfs(self, parent=None, key=None, prune=None):
347        """
348        Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree in
349        the DFS (Depth-first) order.
350
351        Returns:
352            The generator object.
353        """
354        parent = parent or self.parent
355        yield self, parent, key
356        if prune and prune(self, parent, key):
357            return
358
359        for k, v in self.args.items():
360            for node in ensure_collection(v):
361                if isinstance(node, Expression):
362                    yield from node.dfs(self, k, prune)

Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree in the DFS (Depth-first) order.

Returns:

The generator object.

def bfs(self, prune=None): 
364    def bfs(self, prune=None):
365        """
366        Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree in
367        the BFS (Breadth-first) order.
368
369        Returns:
370            The generator object.
371        """
372        queue = deque([(self, self.parent, None)])
373
374        while queue:
375            item, parent, key = queue.popleft()
376
377            yield item, parent, key
378            if prune and prune(item, parent, key):
379                continue
380
381            if isinstance(item, Expression):
382                for k, v in item.args.items():
383                    for node in ensure_collection(v):
384                        if isinstance(node, Expression):
385                            queue.append((node, item, k))

Returns a generator object which visits all nodes in this tree in the BFS (Breadth-first) order.

Returns:

The generator object.

def flatten(self, unnest=True): 
410    def flatten(self, unnest=True):
411        """
412        Returns a generator which yields child nodes who's parents are the same class.
413
414        A AND B AND C -> [A, B, C]
415        """
416        for node, _, _ in self.dfs(prune=lambda n, p, *_: p and not isinstance(n, self.__class__)):
417            if not isinstance(node, self.__class__):
418                yield node.unnest() if unnest else node

Returns a generator which yields child nodes who's parents are the same class.

A AND B AND C -> [A, B, C]

def transform(self, fun, *args, copy=True, **kwargs): 
465    def transform(self, fun, *args, copy=True, **kwargs):
466        """
467        Recursively visits all tree nodes (excluding already transformed ones)
468        and applies the given transformation function to each node.
469
470        Args:
471            fun (function): a function which takes a node as an argument and returns a
472                new transformed node or the same node without modifications. If the function
473                returns None, then the corresponding node will be removed from the syntax tree.
474            copy (bool): if set to True a new tree instance is constructed, otherwise the tree is
475                modified in place.
476
477        Returns:
478            The transformed tree.
479        """
480        node = self.copy() if copy else self
481        new_node = fun(node, *args, **kwargs)
482
483        if new_node is None or not isinstance(new_node, Expression):
484            return new_node
485        if new_node is not node:
486            new_node.parent = node.parent
487            return new_node
488
489        replace_children(new_node, lambda child: child.transform(fun, *args, copy=False, **kwargs))
490        return new_node

Recursively visits all tree nodes (excluding already transformed ones) and applies the given transformation function to each node.

Arguments:
  • fun (function): a function which takes a node as an argument and returns a new transformed node or the same node without modifications. If the function returns None, then the corresponding node will be removed from the syntax tree.
  • copy (bool): if set to True a new tree instance is constructed, otherwise the tree is modified in place.
Returns:

The transformed tree.

def replace(self, expression): 
492    def replace(self, expression):
493        """
494        Swap out this expression with a new expression.
495
496        For example::
497
498            >>> tree = Select().select("x").from_("tbl")
499            >>> tree.find(Column).replace(Column(this="y"))
500            (COLUMN this: y)
501            >>> tree.sql()
502            'SELECT y FROM tbl'
503
504        Args:
505            expression (Expression|None): new node
506
507        Returns:
508            The new expression or expressions.
509        """
510        if not self.parent:
511            return expression
512
513        parent = self.parent
514        self.parent = None
515
516        replace_children(parent, lambda child: expression if child is self else child)
517        return expression

class DerivedTable(Expression): 
658class DerivedTable(Expression):
659    @property
660    def alias_column_names(self):
661        table_alias = self.args.get("alias")
662        if not table_alias:
663            return []
664        column_list = table_alias.assert_is(TableAlias).args.get("columns") or []
665        return [c.name for c in column_list]
666
667    @property
668    def selects(self):
669        alias = self.args.get("alias")
670
671        if alias:
672            return alias.columns
673        return []
674
675    @property
676    def named_selects(self):
677        return [select.output_name for select in self.selects]

class Unionable(Expression): 
680class Unionable(Expression):
681    def union(self, expression, distinct=True, dialect=None, **opts):
682        """
683        Builds a UNION expression.
684
685        Example:
686            >>> import sqlglot
687            >>> sqlglot.parse_one("SELECT * FROM foo").union("SELECT * FROM bla").sql()
688            'SELECT * FROM foo UNION SELECT * FROM bla'
689
690        Args:
691            expression (str | Expression): the SQL code string.
692                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
693            distinct (bool): set the DISTINCT flag if and only if this is true.
694            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
695            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
696        Returns:
697            Union: the Union expression.
698        """
699        return union(left=self, right=expression, distinct=distinct, dialect=dialect, **opts)
700
701    def intersect(self, expression, distinct=True, dialect=None, **opts):
702        """
703        Builds an INTERSECT expression.
704
705        Example:
706            >>> import sqlglot
707            >>> sqlglot.parse_one("SELECT * FROM foo").intersect("SELECT * FROM bla").sql()
708            'SELECT * FROM foo INTERSECT SELECT * FROM bla'
709
710        Args:
711            expression (str | Expression): the SQL code string.
712                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
713            distinct (bool): set the DISTINCT flag if and only if this is true.
714            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
715            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
716        Returns:
717            Intersect: the Intersect expression
718        """
719        return intersect(left=self, right=expression, distinct=distinct, dialect=dialect, **opts)
720
721    def except_(self, expression, distinct=True, dialect=None, **opts):
722        """
723        Builds an EXCEPT expression.
724
725        Example:
726            >>> import sqlglot
727            >>> sqlglot.parse_one("SELECT * FROM foo").except_("SELECT * FROM bla").sql()
728            'SELECT * FROM foo EXCEPT SELECT * FROM bla'
729
730        Args:
731            expression (str | Expression): the SQL code string.
732                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
733            distinct (bool): set the DISTINCT flag if and only if this is true.
734            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
735            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
736        Returns:
737            Except: the Except expression
738        """
739        return except_(left=self, right=expression, distinct=distinct, dialect=dialect, **opts)

Builds a UNION expression.

Example:
>>> import sqlglot
>>> sqlglot.parse_one("SELECT * FROM foo").union("SELECT * FROM bla").sql()
'SELECT * FROM foo UNION SELECT * FROM bla'
Arguments:
  • expression (str | Expression): the SQL code string. If an Expression instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
  • distinct (bool): set the DISTINCT flag if and only if this is true.
  • dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
  • opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
Returns:

Union: the Union expression.

class Column(Condition): 
873class Column(Condition):
874    arg_types = {"this": True, "table": False}
875
876    @property
877    def table(self):
878        return self.text("table")
879
880    @property
881    def output_name(self):
882        return self.name
output_name

Name of the output column if this expression is a selection.

If the Expression has no output name, an empty string is returned.

Example:
>>> from sqlglot import parse_one
>>> parse_one("SELECT a").expressions[0].output_name
'a'
>>> parse_one("SELECT b AS c").expressions[0].output_name
'c'
>>> parse_one("SELECT 1 + 2").expressions[0].output_name
''

class Identifier(Expression): 
1053class Identifier(Expression):
1054    arg_types = {"this": True, "quoted": False}
1055
1056    @property
1057    def quoted(self):
1058        return bool(self.args.get("quoted"))
1059
1060    def __eq__(self, other):
1061        return isinstance(other, self.__class__) and _norm_arg(self.this) == _norm_arg(other.this)
1062
1063    def __hash__(self):
1064        return hash((self.key, self.this.lower()))
1065
1066    @property
1067    def output_name(self):
1068        return self.name
output_name

Name of the output column if this expression is a selection.

If the Expression has no output name, an empty string is returned.

Example:
>>> from sqlglot import parse_one
>>> parse_one("SELECT a").expressions[0].output_name
'a'
>>> parse_one("SELECT b AS c").expressions[0].output_name
'c'
>>> parse_one("SELECT 1 + 2").expressions[0].output_name
''

class Literal(Condition): 
1141class Literal(Condition):
1142    arg_types = {"this": True, "is_string": True}
1143
1144    def __eq__(self, other):
1145        return (
1146            isinstance(other, Literal)
1147            and self.this == other.this
1148            and self.args["is_string"] == other.args["is_string"]
1149        )
1150
1151    def __hash__(self):
1152        return hash((self.key, self.this, self.args["is_string"]))
1153
1154    @classmethod
1155    def number(cls, number) -> Literal:
1156        return cls(this=str(number), is_string=False)
1157
1158    @classmethod
1159    def string(cls, string) -> Literal:
1160        return cls(this=str(string), is_string=True)
1161
1162    @property
1163    def output_name(self):
1164        return self.name
@classmethod
def number(cls, number) -> sqlglot.expressions.Literal: 
1154    @classmethod
1155    def number(cls, number) -> Literal:
1156        return cls(this=str(number), is_string=False)
@classmethod
def string(cls, string) -> sqlglot.expressions.Literal: 
1158    @classmethod
1159    def string(cls, string) -> Literal:
1160        return cls(this=str(string), is_string=True)

1186    def alias_or_name(self):
1187        return self.this.alias_or_name

1189    def on(self, *expressions, append=True, dialect=None, copy=True, **opts):
1190        """
1191        Append to or set the ON expressions.
1192
1193        Example:
1194            >>> import sqlglot
1195            >>> sqlglot.parse_one("JOIN x", into=Join).on("y = 1").sql()
1196            'JOIN x ON y = 1'
1197
1198        Args:
1199            *expressions (str | Expression): the SQL code strings to parse.
1200                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
1201                Multiple expressions are combined with an AND operator.
1202            append (bool): if `True`, AND the new expressions to any existing expression.
1203                Otherwise, this resets the expression.
1204            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expressions.
1205            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
1206            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
1207
1208        Returns:
1209            Join: the modified join expression.
1210        """
1211        join = _apply_conjunction_builder(
1212            *expressions,
1213            instance=self,
1214            arg="on",
1215            append=append,
1216            dialect=dialect,
1217            copy=copy,
1218            **opts,
1219        )
1220
1221        if join.kind == "CROSS":
1222            join.set("kind", None)
1223
1224        return join

class Subqueryable(Unionable): 
1553class Subqueryable(Unionable):
1554    def subquery(self, alias=None, copy=True) -> Subquery:
1555        """
1556        Convert this expression to an aliased expression that can be used as a Subquery.
1557
1558        Example:
1559            >>> subquery = Select().select("x").from_("tbl").subquery()
1560            >>> Select().select("x").from_(subquery).sql()
1561            'SELECT x FROM (SELECT x FROM tbl)'
1562
1563        Args:
1564            alias (str | Identifier): an optional alias for the subquery
1565            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
1566
1567        Returns:
1568            Alias: the subquery
1569        """
1570        instance = _maybe_copy(self, copy)
1571        return Subquery(
1572            this=instance,
1573            alias=TableAlias(this=to_identifier(alias)),
1574        )
1575
1576    def limit(self, expression, dialect=None, copy=True, **opts) -> Select:
1577        raise NotImplementedError
1578
1579    @property
1580    def ctes(self):
1581        with_ = self.args.get("with")
1582        if not with_:
1583            return []
1584        return with_.expressions
1585
1586    @property
1587    def selects(self):
1588        raise NotImplementedError("Subqueryable objects must implement `selects`")
1589
1590    @property
1591    def named_selects(self):
1592        raise NotImplementedError("Subqueryable objects must implement `named_selects`")
1593
1594    def with_(
1595        self,
1596        alias,
1597        as_,
1598        recursive=None,
1599        append=True,
1600        dialect=None,
1601        copy=True,
1602        **opts,
1603    ):
1604        """
1605        Append to or set the common table expressions.
1606
1607        Example:
1608            >>> Select().with_("tbl2", as_="SELECT * FROM tbl").select("x").from_("tbl2").sql()
1609            'WITH tbl2 AS (SELECT * FROM tbl) SELECT x FROM tbl2'
1610
1611        Args:
1612            alias (str | Expression): the SQL code string to parse as the table name.
1613                If an `Expression` instance is passed, this is used as-is.
1614            as_ (str | Expression): the SQL code string to parse as the table expression.
1615                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
1616            recursive (bool): set the RECURSIVE part of the expression. Defaults to `False`.
1617            append (bool): if `True`, add to any existing expressions.
1618                Otherwise, this resets the expressions.
1619            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
1620            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
1621            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
1622
1623        Returns:
1624            Select: the modified expression.
1625        """
1626        alias_expression = maybe_parse(
1627            alias,
1628            dialect=dialect,
1629            into=TableAlias,
1630            **opts,
1631        )
1632        as_expression = maybe_parse(
1633            as_,
1634            dialect=dialect,
1635            **opts,
1636        )
1637        cte = CTE(
1638            this=as_expression,
1639            alias=alias_expression,
1640        )
1641        return _apply_child_list_builder(
1642            cte,
1643            instance=self,
1644            arg="with",
1645            append=append,
1646            copy=copy,
1647            into=With,
1648            properties={"recursive": recursive or False},
1649        )

Append to or set the common table expressions.

1704    def limit(self, expression, dialect=None, copy=True, **opts) -> Select:
1705        """
1706        Set the LIMIT expression.
1707
1708        Example:
1709            >>> select("1").union(select("1")).limit(1).sql()
1710            'SELECT * FROM (SELECT 1 UNION SELECT 1) AS _l_0 LIMIT 1'
1711
1712        Args:
1713            expression (str | int | Expression): the SQL code string to parse.
1714                This can also be an integer.
1715                If a `Limit` instance is passed, this is used as-is.
1716                If another `Expression` instance is passed, it will be wrapped in a `Limit`.
1717            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
1718            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
1719            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
1720
1721        Returns:
1722            Select: The limited subqueryable.
1723        """
1724        return (
1725            select("*")
1726            .from_(self.subquery(alias="_l_0", copy=copy))
1727            .limit(expression, dialect=dialect, copy=False, **opts)
1728        )

1708        Example:
1709            >>> select("1").union(select("1")).limit(1).sql()
1710            'SELECT * FROM (SELECT 1 UNION SELECT 1) AS _l_0 LIMIT 1'
1711
1712        Args:
1713            expression (str | int | Expression): the SQL code string to parse.
1714                This can also be an integer.
1715                If a `Limit` instance is passed, this is used as-is.
1716                If another `Expression` instance is passed, it will be wrapped in a `Limit`.
1717            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
1718            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
1719            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
1720
1721        Returns:
1722            Select: The limited subqueryable.
1723        """
1724        return (
1725            select("*")
1726            .from_(self.subquery(alias="_l_0", copy=copy))
1727            .limit(expression, dialect=dialect, copy=False, **opts)
1728        )

Set the LIMIT expression.

Example:
>>> select("1").union(select("1")).limit(1).sql()
'SELECT * FROM (SELECT 1 UNION SELECT 1) AS _l_0 LIMIT 1'
Arguments:
  • expression (str | int | Expression): the SQL code string to parse. This can also be an integer. If a Limit instance is passed, this is used as-is. If another Expression instance is passed, it will be wrapped in a Limit.
  • dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
  • copy (bool): if False, modify this expression instance in-place.
  • opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
Returns:

Select: The limited subqueryable.

2099    def join(
2100        self,
2101        expression,
2102        on=None,
2103        using=None,
2104        append=True,
2105        join_type=None,
2106        join_alias=None,
2107        dialect=None,
2108        copy=True,
2109        **opts,
2110    ) -> Select:
2111        """
2112        Append to or set the JOIN expressions.
2113
2114        Example:
2115            >>> Select().select("*").from_("tbl").join("tbl2", on="tbl1.y = tbl2.y").sql()
2116            'SELECT * FROM tbl JOIN tbl2 ON tbl1.y = tbl2.y'
2117
2118            >>> Select().select("1").from_("a").join("b", using=["x", "y", "z"]).sql()
2119            'SELECT 1 FROM a JOIN b USING (x, y, z)'
2120
2121            Use `join_type` to change the type of join:
2122
2123            >>> Select().select("*").from_("tbl").join("tbl2", on="tbl1.y = tbl2.y", join_type="left outer").sql()
2124            'SELECT * FROM tbl LEFT OUTER JOIN tbl2 ON tbl1.y = tbl2.y'
2125
2126        Args:
2127            expression (str | Expression): the SQL code string to parse.
2128                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
2129            on (str | Expression): optionally specify the join "on" criteria as a SQL string.
2130                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
2131            using (str | Expression): optionally specify the join "using" criteria as a SQL string.
2132                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
2133            append (bool): if `True`, add to any existing expressions.
2134                Otherwise, this resets the expressions.
2135            join_type (str): If set, alter the parsed join type
2136            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expressions.
2137            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
2138            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
2139
2140        Returns:
2141            Select: the modified expression.
2142        """
2143        parse_args = {"dialect": dialect, **opts}
2144
2145        try:
2146            expression = maybe_parse(expression, into=Join, prefix="JOIN", **parse_args)
2147        except ParseError:
2148            expression = maybe_parse(expression, into=(Join, Expression), **parse_args)
2149
2150        join = expression if isinstance(expression, Join) else Join(this=expression)
2151
2152        if isinstance(join.this, Select):
2153            join.this.replace(join.this.subquery())
2154
2155        if join_type:
2156            natural: t.Optional[Token]
2157            side: t.Optional[Token]
2158            kind: t.Optional[Token]
2159
2160            natural, side, kind = maybe_parse(join_type, into="JOIN_TYPE", **parse_args)  # type: ignore
2161
2162            if natural:
2163                join.set("natural", True)
2164            if side:
2165                join.set("side", side.text)
2166            if kind:
2167                join.set("kind", kind.text)
2168
2169        if on:
2170            on = and_(*ensure_collection(on), dialect=dialect, **opts)
2171            join.set("on", on)
2172
2173        if using:
2174            join = _apply_list_builder(
2175                *ensure_collection(using),
2176                instance=join,
2177                arg="using",
2178                append=append,
2179                copy=copy,
2180                **opts,
2181            )
2182
2183        if join_alias:
2184            join.set("this", alias_(join.this, join_alias, table=True))
2185        return _apply_list_builder(
2186            join,
2187            instance=self,
2188            arg="joins",
2189            append=append,
2190            copy=copy,
2191            **opts,
2192        )

2287        return instance

2289    def ctas(self, table, properties=None, dialect=None, copy=True, **opts) -> Create:
2290        """
2291        Convert this expression to a CREATE TABLE AS statement.
2292
2293        Example:
2294            >>> Select().select("*").from_("tbl").ctas("x").sql()
2295            'CREATE TABLE x AS SELECT * FROM tbl'
2296
2297        Args:
2298            table (str | Expression): the SQL code string to parse as the table name.
2299                If another `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
2300            properties (dict): an optional mapping of table properties
2301            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input table.
2302            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
2303            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input table.
2304
2305        Returns:
2306            Create: the CREATE TABLE AS expression
2307        """
2308        instance = _maybe_copy(self, copy)
2309        table_expression = maybe_parse(
2310            table,
2311            into=Table,
2312            dialect=dialect,
2313            **opts,
2314        )
2315        properties_expression = None
2316        if properties:
2317            properties_expression = Properties.from_dict(properties)
2318
2319        return Create(
2320            this=table_expression,
2321            kind="table",
2322            expression=instance,
2323            properties=properties_expression,
2324        )
2325
2326    def lock(self, update: bool = True, copy: bool = True) -> Select:
2327        """
2328        Set the locking read mode for this expression.
2329
2330        Examples:
2331            >>> Select().select("x").from_("tbl").where("x = 'a'").lock().sql("mysql")
2332            "SELECT x FROM tbl WHERE x = 'a' FOR UPDATE"
2333
2334            >>> Select().select("x").from_("tbl").where("x = 'a'").lock(update=False).sql("mysql")
2335            "SELECT x FROM tbl WHERE x = 'a' FOR SHARE"
2336
2337        Args:
2338            update: if `True`, the locking type will be `FOR UPDATE`, else it will be `FOR SHARE`.
2339            copy: if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
2340
2341        Returns:
2342            The modified expression.
2343        """
2344
2345        inst = _maybe_copy(self, copy)
2346        inst.set("lock", Lock(update=update))
2347
2348        return inst
2349
2350    @property
2351    def named_selects(self) -> t.List[str]:
2352        return [e.output_name for e in self.expressions if e.alias_or_name]
2353
2354    @property
2355    def selects(self) -> t.List[Expression]:
2356        return self.expressions

2122

2124            'SELECT * FROM tbl LEFT OUTER JOIN tbl2 ON tbl1.y = tbl2.y'

2127            expression (str | Expression): the SQL code string to parse.
2128                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
2129            on (str | Expression): optionally specify the join "on" criteria as a SQL string.
2130                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
2131            using (str | Expression): optionally specify the join "using" criteria as a SQL string.
2132                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
2133            append (bool): if `True`, add to any existing expressions.
2134                Otherwise, this resets the expressions.

2138            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
2139
2140        Returns:
2141            Select: the modified expression.
2142        """
2143        parse_args = {"dialect": dialect, **opts}
2144
2145        try:
2146            expression = maybe_parse(expression, into=Join, prefix="JOIN", **parse_args)
2147        except ParseError:
2148            expression = maybe_parse(expression, into=(Join, Expression), **parse_args)
2149
2150        join = expression if isinstance(expression, Join) else Join(this=expression)
2151
2152        if isinstance(join.this, Select):
2153            join.this.replace(join.this.subquery())
2154
2155        if join_type:
2156            natural: t.Optional[Token]
2157            side: t.Optional[Token]
2158            kind: t.Optional[Token]
2159
2160            natural, side, kind = maybe_parse(join_type, into="JOIN_TYPE", **parse_args)  # type: ignore
2161
2162            if natural:
2163                join.set("natural", True)
2164            if side:
2165                join.set("side", side.text)
2166            if kind:
2167                join.set("kind", kind.text)
2168
2169        if on:
2170            on = and_(*ensure_collection(on), dialect=dialect, **opts)
2171            join.set("on", on)
2172

2174            join = _apply_list_builder(
2175                *ensure_collection(using),
2176                instance=join,
2177                arg="using",
2178                append=append,
2179                copy=copy,

2189            append=append,
2190            copy=copy,
2191            **opts,
2192        )

2204                If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
2205                Multiple expressions are combined with an AND operator.
2206            append (bool): if `True`, AND the new expressions to any existing expression.
2207                Otherwise, this resets the expression.
2208            dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expressions.
2209            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
2210            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
2211
2212        Returns:
2213            Select: the modified expression.
2214        """
2215        return _apply_conjunction_builder(
2216            *expressions,
2217            instance=self,
2218            arg="where",
2219            append=append,
2220            into=Where,
2221            dialect=dialect,
2222            copy=copy,
2223            **opts,
2224        )

Example:
>>> Select().select("x").from_("tbl").where("x = 'a' OR x < 'b'").sql()
"SELECT x FROM tbl WHERE x = 'a' OR x < 'b'"

  • *expressions (str | Expression): the SQL code strings to parse. If an Expression instance is passed, it will be used as-is. Multiple expressions are combined with an AND operator.
  • append (bool): if True, AND the new expressions to any existing expression. Otherwise, this resets the expression.
  • dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expressions.
  • copy (bool): if False, modify this expression instance in-place.
  • opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.

Select: the modified expression.

2290        """
2291        Convert this expression to a CREATE TABLE AS statement.

2300            properties (dict): an optional mapping of table properties

2302            copy (bool): if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
2303            opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input table.
2304
2305        Returns:
2306            Create: the CREATE TABLE AS expression
2307        """

2310            table,
2311            into=Table,
2312            dialect=dialect,
2313            **opts,
2314        )
2315        properties_expression = None
2316        if properties:
2317            properties_expression = Properties.from_dict(properties)
2318

2320            this=table_expression,
2321            kind="table",
2322            expression=instance,
2323            properties=properties_expression,
2324        )

def lock( self, update: bool = True, copy: bool = True) -> sqlglot.expressions.Select: 
2326    def lock(self, update: bool = True, copy: bool = True) -> Select:
2327        """
2328        Set the locking read mode for this expression.
2329
2330        Examples:
2331            >>> Select().select("x").from_("tbl").where("x = 'a'").lock().sql("mysql")
2332            "SELECT x FROM tbl WHERE x = 'a' FOR UPDATE"
2333
2334            >>> Select().select("x").from_("tbl").where("x = 'a'").lock(update=False).sql("mysql")

2338            update: if `True`, the locking type will be `FOR UPDATE`, else it will be `FOR SHARE`.
2339            copy: if `False`, modify this expression instance in-place.
2340
2341        Returns:
2342            The modified expression.
2343        """
2344

2346        inst.set("lock", Lock(update=update))
2347
2348        return inst

Set the locking read mode for this expression.

Examples:
>>> Select().select("x").from_("tbl").where("x = 'a'").lock().sql("mysql")
"SELECT x FROM tbl WHERE x = 'a' FOR UPDATE"

>>> Select().select("x").from_("tbl").where("x = 'a'").lock(update=False).sql("mysql")
"SELECT x FROM tbl WHERE x = 'a' FOR SHARE"
Arguments:

  • copy: if False, modify this expression instance in-place.

2569        from sqlglot import parse_one

2573                data_type_exp: t.Optional[Expression] = DataType(this=DataType.Type[dtype.upper()])
2574            else:

2583            raise ValueError(f"Invalid data type: {type(dtype)}. Expected str or DataType.Type")

class Alias(Expression): 
2816class Alias(Expression):
2817    arg_types = {"this": True, "alias": False}
2818
2819    @property
2820    def output_name(self):
2821        return self.alias
output_name

Name of the output column if this expression is a selection.

If the Expression has no output name, an empty string is returned.

Example:
>>> from sqlglot import parse_one
>>> parse_one("SELECT a").expressions[0].output_name
'a'
>>> parse_one("SELECT b AS c").expressions[0].output_name
'c'
>>> parse_one("SELECT 1 + 2").expressions[0].output_name
''
