class Func(Condition): 
2886class Func(Condition):
2887    """
2888    The base class for all function expressions.
2889
2890    Attributes:
2891        is_var_len_args (bool): if set to True the last argument defined in arg_types will be
2892            treated as a variable length argument and the argument's value will be stored as a list.
2893        _sql_names (list): determines the SQL name (1st item in the list) and aliases (subsequent items)
2894            for this function expression. These values are used to map this node to a name during parsing
2895            as well as to provide the function's name during SQL string generation. By default the SQL
2896            name is set to the expression's class name transformed to snake case.
2897    """
2898
2899    is_var_len_args = False
2900
2901    @classmethod
2902    def from_arg_list(cls, args):
2903        if cls.is_var_len_args:
2904            all_arg_keys = list(cls.arg_types)
2905            # If this function supports variable length argument treat the last argument as such.
2906            non_var_len_arg_keys = all_arg_keys[:-1] if cls.is_var_len_args else all_arg_keys
2907            num_non_var = len(non_var_len_arg_keys)
2908
2909            args_dict = {arg_key: arg for arg, arg_key in zip(args, non_var_len_arg_keys)}
2910            args_dict[all_arg_keys[-1]] = args[num_non_var:]
2911        else:
2912            args_dict = {arg_key: arg for arg, arg_key in zip(args, cls.arg_types)}
2913
2914        return cls(**args_dict)
2915
2916    @classmethod
2917    def sql_names(cls):
2918        if cls is Func:
2919            raise NotImplementedError(
2920                "SQL name is only supported by concrete function implementations"
2921            )
2922        if "_sql_names" not in cls.__dict__:
2923            cls._sql_names = [camel_to_snake_case(cls.__name__)]
2924        return cls._sql_names
2925
2926    @classmethod
2927    def sql_name(cls):
2928        return cls.sql_names()[0]
2929
2930    @classmethod
2931    def default_parser_mappings(cls):
2932        return {name: cls.from_arg_list for name in cls.sql_names()}

The base class for all function expressions.

Attributes:
  • is_var_len_args (bool): if set to True the last argument defined in arg_types will be treated as a variable length argument and the argument's value will be stored as a list.
  • _sql_names (list): determines the SQL name (1st item in the list) and aliases (subsequent items) for this function expression. These values are used to map this node to a name during parsing as well as to provide the function's name during SQL string generation. By default the SQL name is set to the expression's class name transformed to snake case.

class Cast(Func): 
3015class Cast(Func):
3016    arg_types = {"this": True, "to": True}
3017
3018    @property
3019    def name(self) -> str:
3020        return self.this.name
3021
3022    @property
3023    def to(self):
3024        return self.args["to"]
3025
3026    @property
3027    def output_name(self):
3028        return self.name
3029
3030    def is_type(self, dtype: DataType.Type) -> bool:
3031        return self.to.is_type(dtype)
output_name

Name of the output column if this expression is a selection.

If the Expression has no output name, an empty string is returned.

Example:
>>> from sqlglot import parse_one
>>> parse_one("SELECT a").expressions[0].output_name
'a'
>>> parse_one("SELECT b AS c").expressions[0].output_name
'c'
>>> parse_one("SELECT 1 + 2").expressions[0].output_name
''
def is_type(self, dtype: sqlglot.expressions.DataType.Type) -> bool: 
3030    def is_type(self, dtype: DataType.Type) -> bool:
3031        return self.to.is_type(dtype)

def maybe_parse( sql_or_expression: str | sqlglot.expressions.Expression, *, into: Union[str, Type[sqlglot.expressions.Expression], Collection[Union[str, Type[sqlglot.expressions.Expression]]], NoneType] = None, dialect: Union[str, sqlglot.dialects.dialect.Dialect, Type[sqlglot.dialects.dialect.Dialect], NoneType] = None, prefix: Optional[str] = None, **opts) -> sqlglot.expressions.Expression: 
3616def maybe_parse(
3617    sql_or_expression: str | Expression,
3618    *,
3619    into: t.Optional[IntoType] = None,
3620    dialect: DialectType = None,
3621    prefix: t.Optional[str] = None,
3622    **opts,
3623) -> Expression:
3624    """Gracefully handle a possible string or expression.
3625
3626    Example:
3627        >>> maybe_parse("1")
3628        (LITERAL this: 1, is_string: False)
3629        >>> maybe_parse(to_identifier("x"))
3630        (IDENTIFIER this: x, quoted: False)
3631
3632    Args:
3633        sql_or_expression: the SQL code string or an expression
3634        into: the SQLGlot Expression to parse into
3635        dialect: the dialect used to parse the input expressions (in the case that an
3636            input expression is a SQL string).
3637        prefix: a string to prefix the sql with before it gets parsed
3638            (automatically includes a space)
3639        **opts: other options to use to parse the input expressions (again, in the case
3640            that an input expression is a SQL string).
3641
3642    Returns:
3643        Expression: the parsed or given expression.
3644    """
3645    if isinstance(sql_or_expression, Expression):
3646        return sql_or_expression
3647
3648    import sqlglot
3649
3650    sql = str(sql_or_expression)
3651    if prefix:
3652        sql = f"{prefix} {sql}"
3653    return sqlglot.parse_one(sql, read=dialect, into=into, **opts)

Gracefully handle a possible string or expression.

Example:
>>> maybe_parse("1")
(LITERAL this: 1, is_string: False)
>>> maybe_parse(to_identifier("x"))
(IDENTIFIER this: x, quoted: False)
Arguments:
  • sql_or_expression: the SQL code string or an expression
  • into: the SQLGlot Expression to parse into
  • dialect: the dialect used to parse the input expressions (in the case that an input expression is a SQL string).
  • prefix: a string to prefix the sql with before it gets parsed (automatically includes a space)
  • **opts: other options to use to parse the input expressions (again, in the case that an input expression is a SQL string).
Returns:

Expression: the parsed or given expression.

def union(left, right, distinct=True, dialect=None, **opts): 
3799def union(left, right, distinct=True, dialect=None, **opts):
3800    """
3801    Initializes a syntax tree from one UNION expression.
3802
3803    Example:
3804        >>> union("SELECT * FROM foo", "SELECT * FROM bla").sql()
3805        'SELECT * FROM foo UNION SELECT * FROM bla'
3806
3807    Args:
3808        left (str | Expression): the SQL code string corresponding to the left-hand side.
3809            If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
3810        right (str | Expression): the SQL code string corresponding to the right-hand side.
3811            If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
3812        distinct (bool): set the DISTINCT flag if and only if this is true.
3813        dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
3814        opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
3815    Returns:
3816        Union: the syntax tree for the UNION expression.
3817    """
3818    left = maybe_parse(sql_or_expression=left, dialect=dialect, **opts)
3819    right = maybe_parse(sql_or_expression=right, dialect=dialect, **opts)
3820
3821    return Union(this=left, expression=right, distinct=distinct)

Initializes a syntax tree from one UNION expression.

Example:
>>> union("SELECT * FROM foo", "SELECT * FROM bla").sql()
'SELECT * FROM foo UNION SELECT * FROM bla'
Arguments:
  • left (str | Expression): the SQL code string corresponding to the left-hand side. If an Expression instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
  • right (str | Expression): the SQL code string corresponding to the right-hand side. If an Expression instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
  • distinct (bool): set the DISTINCT flag if and only if this is true.
  • dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
  • opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
Returns:

Union: the syntax tree for the UNION expression.

def intersect(left, right, distinct=True, dialect=None, **opts): 
3824def intersect(left, right, distinct=True, dialect=None, **opts):
3825    """
3826    Initializes a syntax tree from one INTERSECT expression.
3827
3828    Example:
3829        >>> intersect("SELECT * FROM foo", "SELECT * FROM bla").sql()
3830        'SELECT * FROM foo INTERSECT SELECT * FROM bla'
3831
3832    Args:
3833        left (str | Expression): the SQL code string corresponding to the left-hand side.
3834            If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
3835        right (str | Expression): the SQL code string corresponding to the right-hand side.
3836            If an `Expression` instance is passed, it will be used as-is.
3837        distinct (bool): set the DISTINCT flag if and only if this is true.
3838        dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expression.
3839        opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.
3840    Returns:
3841        Intersect: the syntax tree for the INTERSECT expression.
3842    """
3843    left = maybe_parse(sql_or_expression=left, dialect=dialect, **opts)
3844    right = maybe_parse(sql_or_expression=right, dialect=dialect, **opts)
3845
3846    return Intersect(this=left, expression=right, distinct=distinct)

Initializes a syntax tree from one INTERSECT expression.

Example:
>>> intersect("SELECT * FROM foo", "SELECT * FROM bla").sql()
'SELECT * FROM foo INTERSECT SELECT * FROM bla'
Arguments:
  • left (str | Expression): the SQL code string corresponding to the left-hand side. If an Expression instance is passed, it will be used as-is.

  • opts (kwargs): other options to use to parse the input expressions.

def update( table, properties, where=None, from_=None, dialect=None, **opts) -> sqlglot.expressions.Update: 
3918def update(table, properties, where=None, from_=None, dialect=None, **opts) -> Update:
3919    """
3920    Creates an update statement.
3921
3922    Example:
3923        >>> update("my_table", {"x": 1, "y": "2", "z": None}, from_="baz", where="id > 1").sql()
3924        "UPDATE my_table SET x = 1, y = '2', z = NULL FROM baz WHERE id > 1"
3925
3926    Args:
3927        *properties (Dict[str, Any]): dictionary of properties to set which are
3928            auto converted to sql objects eg None -> NULL
3929        where (str): sql conditional parsed into a WHERE statement
3930        from_ (str): sql statement parsed into a FROM statement
3931        dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expressions.
3932        **opts: other options to use to parse the input expressions.
3933
3934    Returns:
3935        Update: the syntax tree for the UPDATE statement.
3936    """
3937    update = Update(this=maybe_parse(table, into=Table, dialect=dialect))
3938    update.set(
3939        "expressions",
3940        [
3941            EQ(this=maybe_parse(k, dialect=dialect, **opts), expression=convert(v))
3942            for k, v in properties.items()
3943        ],
3944    )
3945    if from_:
3946        update.set(
3947            "from",
3948            maybe_parse(from_, into=From, dialect=dialect, prefix="FROM", **opts),
3949        )
3950    if isinstance(where, Condition):
3951        where = Where(this=where)
3952    if where:
3953        update.set(
3954            "where",
3955            maybe_parse(where, into=Where, dialect=dialect, prefix="WHERE", **opts),
3956        )
3957    return update

Creates an update statement.

Example:
>>> update("my_table", {"x": 1, "y": "2", "z": None}, from_="baz", where="id > 1").sql()
"UPDATE my_table SET x = 1, y = '2', z = NULL FROM baz WHERE id > 1"
Arguments:
  • *properties (Dict[str, Any]): dictionary of properties to set which are auto converted to sql objects eg None -> NULL
  • where (str): sql conditional parsed into a WHERE statement
  • from_ (str): sql statement parsed into a FROM statement
  • dialect (str): the dialect used to parse the input expressions.
  • **opts: other options to use to parse the input expressions.
Returns:

4128def to_interval(interval: str | Literal) -> Interval:
4129    """Builds an interval expression from a string like '1 day' or '5 months'."""
4130    if isinstance(interval, Literal):
4131        if not interval.is_string:
4132            raise ValueError("Invalid interval string.")

def to_table( sql_path: Union[str, sqlglot.expressions.Table, NoneType], **kwargs) -> Optional[sqlglot.expressions.Table]: 
4157def to_table(sql_path: t.Optional[str | Table], **kwargs) -> t.Optional[Table]:
4158    """

def alias_( expression: str | sqlglot.expressions.Expression, alias: str | sqlglot.expressions.Identifier, table: Union[bool, Sequence[str | sqlglot.expressions.Identifier]] = False, quoted: Optional[bool] = None, dialect: Union[str, sqlglot.dialects.dialect.Dialect, Type[sqlglot.dialects.dialect.Dialect], NoneType] = None, **opts): 
4196def alias_(
4197    expression: str | Expression,
4198    alias: str | Identifier,
4199    table: bool | t.Sequence[str | Identifier] = False,
4200    quoted: t.Optional[bool] = None,
4201    dialect: DialectType = None,
4202    **opts,
4203):
4204    """Create an Alias expression.
4205
4206    Example:
4207        >>> alias_('foo', 'bar').sql()
4208        'foo AS bar'
4209
4210        >>> alias_('(select 1, 2)', 'bar', table=['a', 'b']).sql()
4211        '(SELECT 1, 2) AS bar(a, b)'
4212
4213    Args:
4214        expression: the SQL code strings to parse.
4215            If an Expression instance is passed, this is used as-is.
4216        alias: the alias name to use. If the name has
4217            special characters it is quoted.
4218        table: Whether or not to create a table alias, can also be a list of columns.
4219        quoted: whether or not to quote the alias
4220        dialect: the dialect used to parse the input expression.
4221        **opts: other options to use to parse the input expressions.
4222
4223    Returns:
4224        Alias: the aliased expression
4225    """
4226    exp = maybe_parse(expression, dialect=dialect, **opts)
4227    alias = to_identifier(alias, quoted=quoted)
4228
4229    if table:
4230        table_alias = TableAlias(this=alias)
4231        exp.set("alias", table_alias)
4232
4233        if not isinstance(table, bool):
4234            for column in table:
4235                table_alias.append("columns", to_identifier(column, quoted=quoted))
4236
4237        return exp
4238
4239    # We don't set the "alias" arg for Window expressions, because that would add an IDENTIFIER node in
4240    # the AST, representing a "named_window" [1] construct (eg. bigquery). What we want is an ALIAS node
4241    # for the complete Window expression.
4242    #
4243    # [1]: https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/docs/reference/standard-sql/window-function-calls
4244
4245    if "alias" in exp.arg_types and not isinstance(exp, Window):
4246        exp = exp.copy()
4247        exp.set("alias", alias)
4248        return exp
4249    return Alias(this=exp, alias=alias)

Create an Alias expression.

Example:
>>> alias_('foo', 'bar').sql()
'foo AS bar'

>>> alias_('(select 1, 2)', 'bar', table=['a', 'b']).sql()
'(SELECT 1, 2) AS bar(a, b)'
Arguments:
  • expression: the SQL code strings to parse. If an Expression instance is passed, this is used as-is.
  • alias: the alias name to use. If the name has special characters it is quoted.
  • table: Whether or not to create a table alias, can also be a list of columns.
  • quoted: whether or not to quote the alias
  • dialect: the dialect used to parse the input expression.
  • **opts: other options to use to parse the input expressions.
Returns:

Alias: the aliased expression

4303        A cast node.

4305    expression = maybe_parse(expression, **opts)
4306    return Cast(this=expression, to=DataType.build(to, **opts))

def values( values: Iterable[Tuple[Any, ...]], alias: Optional[str] = None, columns: Union[Iterable[str], Dict[str, sqlglot.expressions.DataType], NoneType] = None) -> sqlglot.expressions.Values: 
4328def values(
4329    values: t.Iterable[t.Tuple[t.Any, ...]],
4330    alias: t.Optional[str] = None,
4331    columns: t.Optional[t.Iterable[str] | t.Dict[str, DataType]] = None,
4332) -> Values:
4333    """Build VALUES statement.
4334
4335    Example:
4336        >>> values([(1, '2')]).sql()
4337        "VALUES (1, '2')"
4338
4339    Args:
4340        values: values statements that will be converted to SQL
4341        alias: optional alias
4342        columns: Optional list of ordered column names or ordered dictionary of column names to types.
4343         If either are provided then an alias is also required.
4344         If a dictionary is provided then the first column of the values will be casted to the expected type
4345         in order to help with type inference.
4346
4347    Returns:
4348        Values: the Values expression object
4349    """
4350    if columns and not alias:
4351        raise ValueError("Alias is required when providing columns")
4352    table_alias = (
4353        TableAlias(this=to_identifier(alias), columns=[to_identifier(x) for x in columns])
4354        if columns
4355        else TableAlias(this=to_identifier(alias) if alias else None)
4356    )
4357    expressions = [convert(tup) for tup in values]
4358    if columns and isinstance(columns, dict):
4359        types = list(columns.values())
4360        expressions[0].set(
4361            "expressions",
4362            [cast(x, types[i]) for i, x in enumerate(expressions[0].expressions)],
4363        )
4364    return Values(
4365        expressions=expressions,
4366        alias=table_alias,
4367    )

Build VALUES statement.

Example:
>>> values([(1, '2')]).sql()
"VALUES (1, '2')"
Arguments:
  • values: values statements that will be converted to SQL
  • alias: optional alias
  • columns: Optional list of ordered column names or ordered dictionary of column names to types. If either are provided then an alias is also required. If a dictionary is provided then the first column of the values will be casted to the expected type in order to help with type inference.

def convert(value) -> sqlglot.expressions.Expression: 
4390def convert(value) -> Expression:
4391    """Convert a python value into an expression object.
4392
4393    Raises an error if a conversion is not possible.
4394
4395    Args:
4396        value (Any): a python object
4397
4398    Returns:
4399        Expression: the equivalent expression object
4400    """
4401    if isinstance(value, Expression):
4402        return value
4403    if value is None:
4404        return NULL
4405    if isinstance(value, bool):
4406        return Boolean(this=value)
4407    if isinstance(value, str):
4408        return Literal.string(value)
4409    if isinstance(value, float) and math.isnan(value):
4410        return NULL
4411    if isinstance(value, numbers.Number):
4412        return Literal.number(value)
4413    if isinstance(value, tuple):
4414        return Tuple(expressions=[convert(v) for v in value])
4415    if isinstance(value, list):
4416        return Array(expressions=[convert(v) for v in value])
4417    if isinstance(value, dict):
4418        return Map(
4419            keys=[convert(k) for k in value],
4420            values=[convert(v) for v in value.values()],
4421        )
4422    if isinstance(value, datetime.datetime):
4423        datetime_literal = Literal.string(
4424            (value if value.tzinfo else value.replace(tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc)).isoformat()
4425        )
4426        return TimeStrToTime(this=datetime_literal)
4427    if isinstance(value, datetime.date):
4428        date_literal = Literal.string(value.strftime("%Y-%m-%d"))
4429        return DateStrToDate(this=date_literal)
4430    raise ValueError(f"Cannot convert {value}")

Convert a python value into an expression object.

Raises an error if a conversion is not possible.

Arguments:
  • value (Any): a python object
Returns:

Expression: the equivalent expression object

def replace_children(expression, fun): 
4433def replace_children(expression, fun):
4434    """
4435    Replace children of an expression with the result of a lambda fun(child) -> exp.
4436    """
4437    for k, v in expression.args.items():
4438        is_list_arg = isinstance(v, list)
4439
4440        child_nodes = v if is_list_arg else [v]
4441        new_child_nodes = []
4442
4443        for cn in child_nodes:
4444            if isinstance(cn, Expression):
4445                for child_node in ensure_collection(fun(cn)):
4446                    new_child_nodes.append(child_node)
4447                    child_node.parent = expression
4448                    child_node.arg_key = k
4449            else:
4450                new_child_nodes.append(cn)
4451
4452        expression.args[k] = new_child_nodes if is_list_arg else seq_get(new_child_nodes, 0)

Replace children of an expression with the result of a lambda fun(child) -> exp.

def table_name(table) -> str: 
4473def table_name(table) -> str:
4474    """Get the full name of a table as a string.
4475
4476    Args:
4477        table (exp.Table | str): table expression node or string.
4478
4479    Examples:
4480        >>> from sqlglot import exp, parse_one
4481        >>> table_name(parse_one("select * from a.b.c").find(exp.Table))
4482        'a.b.c'
4483
4484    Returns:
4485        The table name.
4486    """
4487
4488    table = maybe_parse(table, into=Table)
4489
4490    if not table:
4491        raise ValueError(f"Cannot parse {table}")
4492
4493    return ".".join(
4494        part
4495        for part in (
4496            table.text("catalog"),
4497            table.text("db"),
4498            table.name,
4499        )
4500        if part
4501    )

def replace_tables(expression, mapping): 
4504def replace_tables(expression, mapping):
4505    """Replace all tables in expression according to the mapping.
4506
4507    Args:
4508        expression (sqlglot.Expression): expression node to be transformed and replaced.
4509        mapping (Dict[str, str]): mapping of table names.
4510
4511    Examples:
4512        >>> from sqlglot import exp, parse_one
4513        >>> replace_tables(parse_one("select * from a.b"), {"a.b": "c"}).sql()
4514        'SELECT * FROM c'
4515
4516    Returns:
4517        The mapped expression.
4518    """
4519
4520    def _replace_tables(node):
4521        if isinstance(node, Table):
4522            new_name = mapping.get(table_name(node))
4523            if new_name:
4524                return to_table(
4525                    new_name,
4526                    **{k: v for k, v in node.args.items() if k not in ("this", "db", "catalog")},
4527                )
4528        return node
4529
4530    return expression.transform(_replace_tables)

Replace all tables in expression according to the mapping.

def replace_placeholders(expression, *args, **kwargs): 
4533def replace_placeholders(expression, *args, **kwargs):
4534    """Replace placeholders in an expression.
4535
4536    Args:
4537        expression (sqlglot.Expression): expression node to be transformed and replaced.
4538        args: positional names that will substitute unnamed placeholders in the given order.
4539        kwargs: keyword arguments that will substitute named placeholders.
4540
4541    Examples:
4542        >>> from sqlglot import exp, parse_one
4543        >>> replace_placeholders(
4544        ...     parse_one("select * from :tbl where ? = ?"), "a", "b", tbl="foo"
4545        ... ).sql()
4546        'SELECT * FROM foo WHERE a = b'
4547
4548    Returns:
4549        The mapped expression.
4550    """
4551
4552    def _replace_placeholders(node, args, **kwargs):
4553        if isinstance(node, Placeholder):
4554            if node.name:
4555                new_name = kwargs.get(node.name)
4556                if new_name:
4557                    return to_identifier(new_name)
4558            else:
4559                try:
4560                    return to_identifier(next(args))
4561                except StopIteration:
4562                    pass
4563        return node
4564
4565    return expression.transform(_replace_placeholders, iter(args), **kwargs)

Replace placeholders in an expression.

Arguments:
  • expression (sqlglot.Expression): expression node to be transformed and replaced.
  • args: positional names that will substitute unnamed placeholders in the given order.
  • kwargs: keyword arguments that will substitute named placeholders.
Examples:
>>> from sqlglot import exp, parse_one
>>> replace_placeholders(
...     parse_one("select * from :tbl where ? = ?"), "a", "b", tbl="foo"
... ).sql()
'SELECT * FROM foo WHERE a = b'
Returns:

The mapped expression.

def expand( expression: sqlglot.expressions.Expression, sources: Dict[str, sqlglot.expressions.Subqueryable], copy=True) -> sqlglot.expressions.Expression: 
4568def expand(expression: Expression, sources: t.Dict[str, Subqueryable], copy=True) -> Expression:
4569    """Transforms an expression by expanding all referenced sources into subqueries.
4570
4571    Examples:
4572        >>> from sqlglot import parse_one
4573        >>> expand(parse_one("select * from x AS z"), {"x": parse_one("select * from y")}).sql()
4574        'SELECT * FROM (SELECT * FROM y) AS z /* source: x */'
4575
4576    Args:
4577        expression: The expression to expand.
4578        sources: A dictionary of name to Subqueryables.
4579        copy: Whether or not to copy the expression during transformation. Defaults to True.
4580
4581    Returns:
4582        The transformed expression.
4583    """
4584
4585    def _expand(node: Expression):
4586        if isinstance(node, Table):
4587            name = table_name(node)
4588            source = sources.get(name)
4589            if source:
4590                subquery = source.subquery(node.alias or name)
4591                subquery.comments = [f"source: {name}"]
4592                return subquery
4593        return node
4594
4595    return expression.transform(_expand, copy=copy)

Transforms an expression by expanding all referenced sources into subqueries.

Examples:
>>> from sqlglot import parse_one
>>> expand(parse_one("select * from x AS z"), {"x": parse_one("select * from y")}).sql()
'SELECT * FROM (SELECT * FROM y) AS z /* source: x */'

  • expression: The expression to expand.
  • sources: A dictionary of name to Subqueryables.
  • copy: Whether or not to copy the expression during transformation. Defaults to True.

def func( name: str, *args, dialect: Union[str, sqlglot.dialects.dialect.Dialect, Type[sqlglot.dialects.dialect.Dialect], NoneType] = None, **kwargs) -> sqlglot.expressions.Func: 
4598def func(name: str, *args, dialect: DialectType = None, **kwargs) -> Func:
4599    """
4600    Returns a Func expression.
4601
4602    Examples:
4603        >>> func("abs", 5).sql()
4604        'ABS(5)'
4605
4606        >>> func("cast", this=5, to=DataType.build("DOUBLE")).sql()
4607        'CAST(5 AS DOUBLE)'
4608
4609    Args:
4610        name: the name of the function to build.
4611        args: the args used to instantiate the function of interest.
4612        dialect: the source dialect.
4613        kwargs: the kwargs used to instantiate the function of interest.
4614
4615    Note:
4616        The arguments `args` and `kwargs` are mutually exclusive.
4617
4618    Returns:
4619        An instance of the function of interest, or an anonymous function, if `name` doesn't
4620        correspond to an existing `sqlglot.expressions.Func` class.
4621    """
4622    if args and kwargs:
4623        raise ValueError("Can't use both args and kwargs to instantiate a function.")
4624
4625    from sqlglot.dialects.dialect import Dialect
4626
4627    args = tuple(convert(arg) for arg in args)
4628    kwargs = {key: convert(value) for key, value in kwargs.items()}
4629
4630    parser = Dialect.get_or_raise(dialect)().parser()
4631    from_args_list = parser.FUNCTIONS.get(name.upper())
4632
4633    if from_args_list:
4634        function = from_args_list(args) if args else from_args_list.__self__(**kwargs)  # type: ignore
4635    else:
4636        kwargs = kwargs or {"expressions": args}
4637        function = Anonymous(this=name, **kwargs)
4638
4639    for error_message in function.error_messages(args):
4640        raise ValueError(error_message)
4641
4642    return function

Returns a Func expression.

Examples:
>>> func("abs", 5).sql()
'ABS(5)'

>>> func("cast", this=5, to=DataType.build("DOUBLE")).sql()
'CAST(5 AS DOUBLE)'
Arguments:
  • name: the name of the function to build.
  • args: the args used to instantiate the function of interest.
  • dialect: the source dialect.
  • kwargs: the kwargs used to instantiate the function of interest.
Note:

The arguments args and kwargs are mutually exclusive.

Returns:

An instance of the function of interest, or an anonymous function, if name doesn't correspond to an existing sqlglot.expressions.Func class.
